				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k = 7$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M302"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>7</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq155.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, and <inline-formula id="IEq156"><alternatives><tex-math id="M303">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Sigma = \{a,c,t\}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M304"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">{</mml:mo><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>c</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq156.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. It is easy to see that the pBWT implicitly encodes the trie depicted in the right part of Fig. <xref rid="Fig1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>, and such interpretation drives the intuition behind this structure: The trie represents the <italic>reversed</italic> sequences <inline-formula id="IEq157"><alternatives><tex-math id="M305">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R_1[1,k], \ldots , R_6[1,k]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M306"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>…</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mn>6</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq157.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (i.e., read from right to left) in lexicographic order. Leaves (values <inline-formula id="IEq158"><alternatives><tex-math id="M307">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$a_k$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M308"><mml:msub><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq158.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) store the corresponding input indices. The branches correspond to values <inline-formula id="IEq159"><alternatives><tex-math id="M309">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$d_k$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M310"><mml:msub><mml:mi>d</mml:mi><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq159.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (the distance from the root subtracted from <inline-formula id="IEq160"><alternatives><tex-math id="M311">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k+1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M312"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq160.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>). Our main algorithm in this paper makes implicitly a sweep-line over the trie stopping at the branching positions.<fig id="Fig1"><label>Fig. 1</label><caption><p>The pBWT for a set of recombinants <inline-formula id="IEq147"><alternatives><tex-math id="M313">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathcal {R}} = \{R_1, \ldots , R_6\}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M314"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">R</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">{</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>…</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mn>6</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq147.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> with <inline-formula id="IEq148"><alternatives><tex-math id="M315">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k = 7$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M316"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>7</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq148.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and the corresponding trie containing the reversed strings <inline-formula id="IEq149"><alternatives><tex-math id="M317">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R_1[1,k], \ldots , R_6[1,k]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M318"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>…</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mn>6</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq149.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> in lexicographic order</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Fig1_HTML" id="MO4"/></fig></p>
          <p>Durbin [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR20">20</xref>] showed that <inline-formula id="IEq161"><alternatives><tex-math id="M319">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$a_k$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M320"><mml:msub><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq161.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq162"><alternatives><tex-math id="M321">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$d_k$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M322"><mml:msub><mml:mi>d</mml:mi><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq162.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> can be computed from <inline-formula id="IEq163"><alternatives><tex-math id="M323">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$a_{k-1}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M324"><mml:msub><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq163.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq164"><alternatives><tex-math id="M325">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$d_{k-1}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M326"><mml:msub><mml:mi>d</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq164.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> in <italic>O</italic>(<italic>m</italic>) time on the binary alphabet. Mäkinen and Norri [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR21">21</xref>] further generalized the construction for integer alphabets of size <italic>O</italic>(<italic>m</italic>), as in our case. For the sake of completeness, we describe in this subsection the generalized solution [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR21">21</xref>] (see Algorithm 1), which serves then as a basis for our main algorithm. We also present a modification of this solution (see Algorithm 2), which, albeit seems to be slightly inferior in theory (we could prove only <inline-formula id="IEq165"><alternatives><tex-math id="M327">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$O(m\log |\Sigma |)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M328"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mo>log</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq165.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> time upper bound), showed better performance in practice and thus, as we believe, is interesting by itself. <graphic position="anchor" xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Figa_HTML" id="MO13"/>
<graphic position="anchor" xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Figb_HTML" id="MO14"/>
</p>
        </sec>
        <sec id="FPar3">
          <title>
            <bold>Lemma 2</bold>
          </title>
          <p id="Par36"><italic>The arrays</italic><inline-formula id="IEq166"><alternatives><tex-math id="M329">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$a_k[1,m]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M330"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13015_2019_147_Article_IEq166.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula><italic>and</italic><inline-formula id="IEq167"><alternatives><tex-math id="M331">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
